<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-771  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 771.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Jan 1989 v14 n1 p253(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber vs. metal; mix, match, and choose between fiber-optic andmetallic cables. (includes related article on plastic fiber-opticcable) (In Depth - PC Communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bryce, James Y.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optics has yet to be accepted by the computer industry foruse in local area networks (LAN), but after careful considerationof this medium's costs, performance and cost-to-benefit ratio, itmay prove to be the best choice, if not for the entire network,then for significant portions of one.andP;  When contrasting fiber withmetallic cables, usually twisted-pair or coaxial, fiber wins onalmost every point.andP;  Although fiber-optic cable is thought to beprohibitively expensive it has the same costs, $0.5 to $1 perfoot, as metallic cable.andP;  Installing fiber optic cable does costbecause a higher skill level is required, and few qualifiedfiber-optic installers exist so they can charge more.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTwisted PairComparisonCablesCoaxial cablesTelecommunicationsLocal Area Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Fiber-optic performance as compared with twisted-pair and coaxial.andO;(table)The change in signal levels over metallic cable. (chart)Fiber-optic costs versus those for twisted-pair and coaxialcables. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>